<H3> <TI>   ANC Urges Government Intervention in Homeland </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MB1003095694 Johannesburg SAPA in English 0913 GMT 10 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB1003095694 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by C. Molusi] </F>
  [Text] Johannesburg March 10 SAPA--African National 
Congress [ANC] Secretary General Cyril Ramaphosa on Thursday [10 
March] called for immediate South African Government 
intervention in Bophuthatswana to protect lives. Mr Ramaphosa 
would not be drawn on the form of intervention. 
  ANC President Nelson Mandela would speak to State President 
F.W. de Klerk on Thursday about the crisis in Bophuthatswana and 
impress on him the urgency of taking decisive steps against the 
homeland, Mr Ramaphosa added. He said the crisis in 
Bophuthatswana was such that it could not wait for a 
Transitional Executive Council meeting on Monday. 
  Mr Ramaphosa said an emergency session of the executive 
council might be called, but the South African Government was 
fully entitled to give protection to its citizens in 
Bophuthtastwana -- in consultation with the ANC. "We are 
concerned that unless action is taken immediately, we might be 
facing a situation which could be worse than Bisho," he said, 
alluding to a massacre in Ciskei in 1992. 
  "All indications are now that it is quite possible that the 
security forces in Bophuthatswana will start panicking and open 
fire at randonm at people who are protesting legitimately for 
their human rights." 
  Mr Ramaphosa said: "It is quite clear to us that (President) 
Lucas Mangope has put himself on a collision course with the 
people of South Africa as whole." 
  The executive council had been approached by the Civil 
Servants Association of Bophuthatswana for talks on 
rationalisation, job prospects, salaries and pensions. Mr 
Ramaphosa said Bophuthatswana would cease to exist after April 
27 and it was important that administration and government 
services in that area should continue. 

</TEXT>

