<H3> <TI>   Military Intervention in Bophuthatswana Rejected </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MB1003123494 Johannesburg Radio South Africa Network in 
English 1100 GMT 10 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB1003123494 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg Radio South Africa Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] The ANC [African National Congress] has again 
called on the government to intervene in Bophuthatswana. ANC 
Secretary General Cyril Ramaphosa said that he expected the 
Transitional Executive Council to implement a range of steps 
aimed at bringing President Mangope's government to heel. 
[passage omitted] 
  However, Foreign Affairs Minister Pik Botha has said that 
the 
government will not consider military intervention in 
Bophuthatswana while South African interests and nationals are 
not threatened. Mr. Botha was responding to a statement during 
Radio Today by a senior ANC official who said that it was the 
government's responsibility to deal with the present unrest 
situation in the state. 

