<H3> <TI>   IEC, Freedom Front Discuss Election Participation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MB0903175794 Johannesburg SAPA in English 1735 GMT 9 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB0903175794 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Johannesburg March 9 SAPA -- The rightist Freedom 
Front was considering taking part in the April elections -- but 
had not yet submitted candidate lists, Independent Electoral 
Commission [IEC] Chairman Justice Johan Kriegler said on 
Wednesday [9 March] night. 
  Three unidentified representatives of the front were holed 
up 
in a meeting with electoral officials for three hours on 
Wednesday afternoon and evening after the close of the 4.30pm 
deadline for parties to submit a candidates' list. 
  The judge -- who also brushed aside concern about deadlines 
-- met the Freedom Front offcials, but would not comment on his 
discussions. 
  Justice Kriegler said he had also been in touch with the 
Inkatha Freedom Party which he said had "not yet" submitted its 
lists. The judge brushed aside concern about all deadlines 
imposed by the Electoral Act."The deadline is a journalistic 
concern and we are in [words indistinct] determine whether 
somebody has exceeded the speed limit. We are trying to organise 
an election of national reconciliation." 
  The judge added the law could be amended retrospectively if 
all the political parties agreed. 
  The Freedom Front officials arrived shortly before [words 
indistinct]. 
  Earlier in the day 25 parties, including the National Party, 
African National Congress, the Pan Africanist Congress, [words 
indistinct] party, minority groups as well as regional and 
special interest parties, submitted candidate lists. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

