<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Investigation of Air Force Weapons Theft Continues </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MB0903163594 Johannesburg SAPA in English 1555 GMT 9 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB0903163594 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Pretoria March 9 SAPA -- A South African Air Force 
[SAAF] flight sergeant, detained in connection with the weekend 
arms theft from an air force depot at Voortrekkerhoogte, 
Pretoria, has been released, the SAAF said on Wednesday [9 
March]. The SAAF member was detained on Tuesday in terms of the 
military discipline code. He was giving his "full co-operation" 
in the investigation, a statement said. 
  An SAAF spokesman would not be drawn on suggestions that at 
least three SAAF members could soon be detained after the theft 
of what the SAAF called "about 50 light weapons". 
  Police spokesman Evan Johnson said on Wednesday a "large 
amount" of weapons seemed at this stage to be missing. The exact 
figure was still being determined through stock checks. 
  All possible motives were being investigated and it was not 
clear if the thest had a political connotation, Capt Johnson 
said. A reward of up to R100,000 [rand] had been posted for 
information leading to the arrest and conviction of those 
responsible. 
  The African National Congress has expressed concern at the 
regularity of raids on SADF [South African Defense Force] arms 
depositories, especially in the light of the fact that South 
African Communist Party General Secretary Chris Hani was 
assassinated with a weapon stolen from the SADF. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

