<F P=101> Namibia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russian Plane Grounded Over Supplies for UNITA </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MB1003092994 Johannesburg SAPA in English 0859 GMT 10 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB1003092994 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Windhoek March 10 SAPA -- A Russian cargo aircraft 
has been grounded at Rundu in northern Namibia following 
Namibian and Angolan claims that the medical supplies on board 
are bound for UNITA [National Union for the Total Independence 
of Angola] rebels in Angola. 
  Police have also confiscated radio equipment from the 
aircraft, saying there are no valid transportation permits for 
the equipment. The grounding was authorised by the district 
commissioner of Namibia's north-eastern region, Mr Ben Haingura, 
after a request from Angolan authorities. 
  The Antonov-26's pilot, Mr Oleg Pantiuhia, denied the claims 
of supplying UNITA and said his employer, Ecomex, supplied 
medical equipment to "Angolan civilians". 

</TEXT>

