<F P=100> WEST AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Nigeria </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rights Group Urges Amicable Solution to Dispute </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AB1003133094 Paris AFP in English 2200 GMT 9 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AB1003133094 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Lagos, 9 March (AFP) -- A war between Nigerian 
and Cameroon over ownership of the Bakassi peninsula would not 
be only a diversion but also "a misdirected and ill-advised 
aggression", a Lagos-based human rights group said here 
Wednesday [9 March]. 
  The Committee for the Defence of Human Rights (CDHR) said in 
a statement that leaders of the two neighbouring nations "can 
and should seek" an amicable solution to the conflict in order 
to avoid imminent "war that now stares both countries in the 
face" "We cannot at this time afford to go on a war whose 
disastrous end no one can predict", the statement said. At a 
time when Nigerians and Cameroonians were "wallowing in abject 
poverty" and yearning for democracy, it was unfortunate that 
leaders of the two nations are "warming up for war", it 
continued. [passage omitted] 
  Wole Soyinka, the 1986 Nobel literature laureate, warned 
earlier in the week that it would be senseless for the two West 
African countries to go to war over a border dispute. [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

