<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Violence Descends on Bophuthatswana as Government Flees </TI></H3>
<H4>   Mangope Leaves Mmbatho </H4>
<F P=102> MB1003180994 London BBC World Service in English 1740 GMT 10 
Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB1003180994 </F>
<F P=104>  London BBC World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "African News" program] </F>
  [Text] Reports from the nominally independent South African 
homeland of Bophuthatswana say that thousands of people have 
looted a shopping center in the capital, Mmabatho, in the latest 
antigovernment demonstrations. The police appear not to have 
intervened. Mr. Mangope's helicopter is reported to have left 
the capital, Mmabatho. Some reports say Mr. Mangope was aboard 
but this hasn't been confirmed. 
  There have been several days of antigovernment protests in 
Bophuthatswana and earlier today, about 200 policemen said they 
supported calls for the homeland to be incorporated into South 
Africa. Mr. Mangope has been resisting demands that 
Bophuthatswana should take part in South Africa's first 
nonracial elections next month. The African National Congress 
[ANC] had called for the South African security forces to 
intervene to stop the unrest. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-641 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drafr048_c_94003" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-AFR-94-048 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  11 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Violence Descends on Bophuthatswana as Government Flees </TI></H3>
<H4>   ANC Accused of Involvement </H4>
<F P=102> MB1003183794 Johannesburg SAPA in English 1823 GMT 10 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB1003183794 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Mmabatho March 10 SAPA -- Bophuthatswana's President 
Lucas Mangope reportedly fled the capital Mmabatho on Thursday 
[10 March] evening amid signs a popular uprising was underway in 
the embattled homeland where thousands of people took to the 
streets, looting and burning shops. 
  South Africa's Ambassador Tjaart van der Walt told SAPA he 
had spoken at about 6.30pm to President Mangope, who said he was 
going to his country residence at Motsepi. "I have not contacted 
him there yet," the Dr van der Walt. [sentence as received] 
  In another development, the Freedom Alliance said on 
Thursday 
it was suspending negotiations with the South African Government 
and the African National Congress [ANC] to protest against the 
ANC's involvement in upheavals in Bophuthatswana. "The leaders 
of the Freedom Alliance have therefore decided that all 
negotiations, mediation, submission of (election) candidate 
lists and efforts by the Freedom Alliance to rejoin the process 
will be stopped forthwith until the ANC has stopped the action 
in Bophuthatswana," Afrikaner Volksfront [Afrikaner National 
Front] leader General Constand Viljoen said in a statement. 
  Waving ANC and SA Communist Party placards, thousands of 
people took to the streets of Mmabatho on Thursday, apparently 
spurred by a march by about 300 policemen to the SA Embassy to 
demand reincorporation of Bophuthatswna into South Africa. Later 
in the afternoon there were reports homeland police had gone on 
strike. 
  Homeland soldiers fired teargas at thousands of protesters 
who stormed and looted the Megacity shopping complex in 
Mmabatho. The soldiers later surrounded the complex to keep the 
looters at bay. 
  Also on Thursday evening protesters set fire to a general 
store in Mmabatho belonging to the homeland's police chief, 
General PJ Seleke. The store is near the University of 
Bophuthatswana where students have clashed with police in the 
past few days. 
  "They opened the gas taps and threw a match into the store 
and it just went up," one of the people outside blazing building 
told SAPA. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

