<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Violence Descends on Bophuthatswana as Government Flees </TI></H3>
<H4>   AWB Members Gather in Mmbatho </H4>
<F P=102> MB1003212994 Johannesburg SAPA in English 2104 GMT 10 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB1003212994 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Lew Elias] </F>
  [Text] Mmabatho March 10 SAPA -- White people in army 
camouflage uniform have entered the fray in riotous 
Bophuthatswana. The white men kept protesters away from the 
looted Megacity shopping complex and the University of 
Bophuthatswana in Mmabatho on Thursday [10 March] night. 
  It was not known who the white men were. The South African 
Defence Force earlier on Thursday night denied that its had sent 
soldiers to the homeland. 
  Gunshots were heard in the vicinity of the university, where 
there was a group of about 100 white men in camouflage. 
  Meanwhile, members of the rightwing Afrikaner 
Weerstandsbeweging [AWB, Afrikaner Resistance Movement] have 
arrived in Mmabatho and are believed to be converging at the 
city's prison. 
  An SABC [South African Broadcasting Corporation] television 
crew was stopped by a large group of AWB members. The keys for 
their vehicle were taken and thrown away, their film confiscated 
and destroyed and the crew left stranded on the road between 
Mmabatho and Zeerust. 
  Acccording to SABC-TV producer Nan Roux the team had been 
harassed and she was mobilising people from the Mmbatho Sun 
Hotel to rescue the stranded crew. 
  ITN [Independent Television News] reporter James Brittan 
said 
he had seen a group of about 30 white farmers in bakkies about 
10km outside Mmabatho. "They were all driving farm vehicles and 
we asssume they were AWB members. They then turned off the main 
road and we followed them for a short way before returning to 
Mmabatho," he said. 
  SA Police said on Thursday night they are aware that of a 
group of at least 200 rightwingers had moved from Zeerust to a 
place close to Bophuthatswana. 
  Western Transvaal police spokesman Capt Koos Degenaar told 
SAPA police were aware of the rightwing movements. 
  The SAP [South African Police] was not able to ascertain 
exactly where the group was gathering and therefore could not 
act. 
  He said police in the Western Transvaal had "sharpened our 
patrols along the Bophuthatswana borders because of all the 
unrest" in the homeland. 
  He said the SAP could not act outside of South Africa but 
were making an extra effort to patrol the borders. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

