<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Violence Descends on Bophuthatswana as Government Flees </TI></H3>
<H4>   AWB Confirms 5,000 Sent to Mmbatho </H4>
<F P=102> MB1103064694 Johannesburg SAPA in English 2210 GMT 10 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB1103064694 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Rooigrond, Bophuthatswana March 10 SAPA -- A convoy 
of 20 vehicles carrying heavily armed khaki-clad rightwingers 
heading for Bophuthatswana's capital Mmabatho was diverted at a 
roadblock at Rooigrond, near the SA [South Africa] border, at 
about 11.30 PM on Thursday [10 March]. The convoy of cars and 
bakkies [pickup trucks] were each occupied by at least four or 
five khaki-clad men. 
  According to SA Police manning the roadblock at Rooigrond, 
about 20km from Mmabatho, the convoy was re-routed to Buhrmons 
Drift. 
  According to police, the road through Buhmorns Drift did 
offer access to Mmbatho. As no law had been broken, the convoy 
was allowed to proceed. 
  [Johannesburg SAPA in English on 11 March at 0745 GMT 
reports 
that "the Afrikaner Weerstandbeweging [Resistance Movement -- 
AWB] has between 4,000 and 5,000 men in Mmabatho, AWB Gen Steven 
Meninger told journalists on Friday morning. The men had made 
the Bophuthatswana Air Force base their headquarters and they 
were deployed all over town, he said. AWB leader Eugene 
Terreblanche is also said to be in Mmabatho to take charge of 
his men."] 

</TEXT>

