<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Violence Descends on Bophuthatswana as Government Flees </TI></H3>
<H4>   SADF Troops Move In 11 Mar </H4>
<F P=102> MB1103065594 Johannesburg SAPA in English 0358 GMT 11 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB1103065594 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Johannesburg March 11 SAPA -- A contingent of SA 
[South African] Defence Force [SADF] troops has moved in to 
Mmabatho to take up position in the grounds of the South African 
Embassy, Foreign Affairs Minister Pik Botha said in a statement 
early Friday [11 March] morning. 
  Mr Botha said the intention was that the force would be 
prepared to maintain law and order and to protect SA citizens 
and their interests. He said the SA ambassador in the 
Bophuthatswana capital had not been able to make contact with 
Bophuthatswana President Lucas Mangope or any of his ministers. 
With the outbreak of attacks and looting on Thursday, South 
African interests were being seriously threatened. 
  Information that right wing elements were on their way to 
Mmabatho had also reached the SA government. "Against this 
background the president, after consultation with relevant 
minsiters and security forces, decided that a component of the 
SA army should take up a position in the grounds of the SA 
embassy in Mmabatho during (Thursday) night. 
  "The objective of this deployement is first to ensure that 
the SA representattvies and their families be protected against 
possible attack of any kind. Secondly it is the intention that 
the component should be on hand to maintain law and order and to 
protect SA citizens and their interests should the situation 
deteriorate." 
  Mr Botha said the government would not hesitate to take 
similar steps in any other of the republic's nominally 
independent states. 
  The Transitional Executive Council was being kept informed 
of 
developments, he said. 

</TEXT>

