<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-650 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drafr048_c_94012" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-AFR-94-048 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  11 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Violence Descends on Bophuthatswana as Government Flees </TI></H3>
<H4>   AVF Leader Fears MK-AWB Clashes </H4>
<F P=102> MB1103065794 Johannesburg SAPA in English 0538 GMT 11 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB1103065794 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Mmabatho March 11 SAPA -- There might be a change in 
the pattern of shooting in Mmabatho on Friday [11 March] if 
rightwingers clashed with the reported 30 or 40 Umkhonto we 
Sizwe [Spear of the Nation -- MK] members who had been 
despatched to the area, Afrikaner Volksfront [National Front] 
General Constand Viljoen warned on Friday. 
  Speaking on SABC [South African Broadcasting Corporation] 
television, he said: "We had a specific request not to deploy 
the Afrikaner Weerstandsbeweging (AWB) in the area." Troops 
from the farming community were therefore sent into Mmabatho. 
  Gen Viljoen said he was aware the AWB had arrived in 
Bophuthatswana but after discussions with the Bophuthatswana 
government he had, at 4.45 AM Friday, asked the AWB to withdraw. 
  He was aware that a political, and not military, solution 
was 
needed in Bophuthatswana but the territory needed stability for 
that to take place. 
  The Bophuthatswana government should be allowed to make a 
decision about the territory's continued independence without 
being intimidated, he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

