<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Violence Descends on Bophuthatswana as Government Flees </TI></H3>
<H4>   Unrest Spreading to Winterveld, Mabopane </H4>
<F P=102> MB1103095494 Johannesburg SAPA in English 0922 GMT 11 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB1103095494 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by N. Patterton] </F>
  [Text] Pretoria March 11 SAPA--Bophuthatswana areas 
north-west of Pretoria such as Winterveld, Mabopane and 
Garankuwa were torn by violence, looting and shooting on 
Thursday [10 March] night and Friday morning, according to 
witnesses. Reports said 20 people had been admitted to 
Garankuwa hospital, five with gunshot wounds. 
  The SABC [South African Broadcasting Corporation] reported 
that one victim died and that there was rioting at Hlabane near 
Rustenburg. 
  Residents in Winterveld in central Bophuthatswana reported 
shooting through the night, and that shopping complexes had been 
looted and torched. Bophuthatswana police shot at people in the 
streets, they said. Witnesses in Winterveld claimed that 
homeland police participated in the looting. 
  No comment on any of these events could be obtained from the 
Bophuthatswanan police headquarters in Mmabatho. 
  Earlier, SABC [South African Broadcasting Corporation] news 
reported that a section of a multi-million rand shopping complex 
in Mabopane in Bophuthatswana was set alight on Friday morning. 
  This brought to three the number of buildings torched since 
Thursday night, the first two being government administration 
buildings. 

</TEXT>

