<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Violence Descends on Bophuthatswana as Government Flees </TI></H3>
<H4>   AWB, Bophuthatswana Defense Force Clash </H4>
<F P=102> MB1103113594 Johannesburg SAPA in English 1036 GMT 11 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB1103113594 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by L. Elias] </F>
  [Text] Mmabatho March 11 SAPA--The Bophuthatswana Defence 
Force [BDF] is running a large group of armed right-wingers out 
of Mmabatho, STAR photographer Ken Oosterbroek said on Friday 
[11 March]. 
  ITN [International Television Network] Reporter James 
Brittan 
told SAPA there was a "wall-to-wall" Afrikaner 
Weerstandsbeweging [Resistance Movement -- AWB] presence in 
downtown Mafikeng and continuous gunfire from the central 
business district. "It is a running firefight," he said. 
  According to CNN news, the AWB has refused to pull out of 
Bophuthatswana as "this is our land and we are staying". 
  There was fighting in dowtown Mafikeng on Friday between the 
AWB and the BDF, with one AWB member killed and two civilians 
caught in crossfire. 
  SUNDAY TIMES Reporter Ray Hartley described the scene "war". 
There was sustained, continuous gunfire for more than four 
minutes. "There have been casualties. One AWB guy has been 
killed and two civilians. There are plenty of people wounded," 
Mr Hartley told SAPA. 
  Surrounding townships and Mafikeng were battlefields, 
journalists told SAPA after returning from trips to Mmabatho and 
Mafikeng. 
  "The AWB have moved beyond Mafikeng," Mr Hartley said, 
adding 
that hundreds of right-wingers had left town. A continuous 
stream of vehicles filled with the right-wingers left the 
Mmabatho area soon after noon, heading towards Mafikeng and 
Lichtenberg in the Western Transvaal. 

</TEXT>

