<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on News Conference </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MB1103143494 Johannesburg SAPA in English 1414 GMT 11 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB1103143494 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Erna van Wyk] </F>
  [Text] Pretoria March 11 SAPA -- The African National 
Congress [ANC] should take partial responsibility for the damage 
and unrest in Bophuthatswana, President F W de Klerk told a news 
conference in Pretoria on Friday [11 March]. He added that 
within a few hours there would be definite arrangements between 
the South African Government and Bophuthatswana for the South 
African Defence Force [SADF] to move into bophuthatswana and 
help stabilise it. 
  The news conference heard SADF forces had been deployed in 
Mmabatho and more were on standby. 
  Mr de Klerk welcomed Bophuthatswana President Lucas 
Mangope's 
decision to register for the elections and said he hoped this 
would have an immediate stabilising effect on the territory. He 
rejected the perception that the unrest had brought about Mr 
Mangope's decision to register, and attributed this to the 
continued negotiations between the Bophuhatswana government, the 
South African Government and other interested parties. 
  SADF Chief Gen Georg Meiring and South African Police 
Commissioner Johan van der Merwe left after lunch to appraise 
the situation in Bophuthatswana and would also hold talks with 
Bophuthatswanan's chiefs of police and Bophuthatswana Defence 
Force. 
  On the violence and looting that erupted in the areas along 
the border of South Africa and Bophuthatswana north of Pretoria, 
Mr de Klerk said security forces had been deployed where 
warranted. 
  Mr de Klerk said he had been in contact with African 
National 
Congress President Nelson Mandela, speaking to him twice on 
Friday. Mr de Klerk said there had been good co-operation 
between his government and the African National Congress [ANC]. 
  The leadership of the ANC had acted responsibly and "we 
worked well together". The same could not be said, however, of 
the ANC supporters and their surrogate organisations. 
  Information at hand pointed to their involvement in creating 
the situation and in fostering a volatile spirit. 
  Minister of Defence Kobie Coetsee said one facet of the 
unrest was the presence of elements of private armies. 

</TEXT>

