<H3> <TI>   Ciskei Soldiers Reportedly Mutiny Over Pensions </TI></H3>
<H4>   Law Minister on `Talk of a Coup' </H4>
<F P=102> MB1003145694 Johannesburg SAPA in English 1440 GMT 10 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB1003145694 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by B. MacLennan] </F>
  [Text] Berlin March 10 SAPA -- Law and Order Minister 
Hernus Kriel said on Thursday [10 March] afternoon there was 
talk that a coup had begun in Bisho, Ciskei. 
  Speaking in Eastern Cape town of Berlin, he apologised for 
cutting his electioneering meeting short. "There are problems in 
the Ciskei at the moment in Bisho. There's talk of a coup." 
  He said he was was going to see what was going on. "Let's 
hold thumbs it doesn't lead to bloodshed." 
  However, spot telephone inquiries to people working in 
Bisho late on Thursday afternoon did not reveal anything unusual 
in the Ciskei capital. 
  A lawyer in Bisho told SAPA "nothing extraordinary" was 
happening. He said he had a bird's eye view of the town's main 
etreet from a hill in neighbouring King William's Town. 
  A businesswoman said she had heard "talk of toyi-toying 
[protest dancing] by NEHAWU (the National Education, Health and 
Allied Workers Union". 
  Soldiers had been coming and going throughout the day, but 
there was nothing unusual in that, she added. 
  A local bottle store was "as busy as heck" shortly before 
5pm, and civil servants were among the customers. 

</TEXT>

