<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ciskei Soldiers Reportedly Mutiny Over Pensions </TI></H3>
<H4>   Gqozo Holds Talks With Troops </H4>
<F P=102> MB1003170894 Johannesburg SAPA in English 1642 GMT 10 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB1003170894 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Bisho March 10 SAPA -- Ciskei military ruler 
Brigadier Oupa Gqozo was locked in talks with troops of his 
first battalion at a military base outside Bisho on Thursday [10 
March] after a South African cabinet minister expressed concern 
earlier in the day about the possibility of a coup in the 
independent territory. 
  Ciskei police who were monitoring the base from a dirt road 
nearby said the brigadier entered the base about 3pm. He was 
still there at 5.30pm. A guard at the base gate said there were 
"problems being experienced by us as soldiers" and that the 
brigadier was addressing them. 
  Earlier in the day SAPA reported that South Africa Law and 
Order Minister Hernus Kriel, speaking in Berlin on an Eastern 
Cape election tour, apologised for cutting short his address and 
told his audience: 
  "I'm talking about the Ciskei, various problems in the 
Ciskei, in Bisho. There's talk of a coup. I'm not involved in 
the coup but ii am involved in the security side." 
  The National Party politician then left for Bisho, Ciskei's 
capital, to monitor the situation. 
  Mr Kriel's spokesman, Craig Kotze, said the minister's 
remarks had to be seen "against the background of increasing 
tension in the homeland". He added: 
  "Obviously we will be monitoring the situation to see the 
lives, property and interests of South African citizens (in 
Ciskei) are not directly threatened." 
  Ciskei TEC [Transitional Executive Council] member Mickey 
Webb said any rumour of a coup in the independent territory was 
"devoid of all truth". 
  Quoting South Africa's ambassador to Ciskei, Pieter Goosen, 
Mr Webb claimed he had been told Mr Kriel had denied making any 
reference to a possible coup in Ciskei. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

