<DOCNO> FBIS3-675 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drafr048_c_94038" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-AFR-94-048 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  11 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   AVF's Viljoen on Talks Halt </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MB1003194794 Johannesburg SABC TV 1 Network in English 1800 
GMT 10 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB1003194794 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SABC TV 1 Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The leaders of the Freedom Alliance have decided 
that all negotiations, mediation, and submission of candidate 
lists for the elections by the alliance should stop immediately. 
Afrikaner Volksfront [National Front] General Constand Viljoen 
said the alliance will resume negotiations once the ANC [African 
National Congress]-SACP [South African Communist Party] alliance 
recognizes the sovereignty of Bophuthatswana. Johan Classen 
reports: 
  [Begin recording] [Classen] General Viljoen held discussions 
with President Mangope in Mbabatho earlier today, before the 
decision was taken by the Freedom Alliance. He said the 
situation in Bophuthatswana was totally unacceptable. He called 
the violence total terrorism. 
  [Viljoen] Well, to start off, we don't rejoin the process. 
And I think if that is the case, we must seriously in this 
country start talking and considering partition of the country, 
because if there is no way of finding a solution by 
negotiations, to jointly stay and share this country, then we 
must really start thinking about partition of the country. 
  [Classen] Gen. Viljoen predicted that the same situation 
might develop in KwaZulu, and at a later stage in the Republic. 
He also explained why military intervention, be it by the South 
African Defense Force or the AWB [Afrikaner Resistance 
Movement], was the wrong option. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

