<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   South African Press Review for 11 Mar </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MB1103134594 </F>
<F P=103> MB1103134594 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:BFN 

  [Editorial Report] 
<H6>  THE CITIZEN </H6>
  TEC ANC Vehicle for Action Against `Enemies' -- Johannesburg 
THE CITIZEN in English on 10 March in its page-6 editorial says 
it expected the "African National Congress (ANC)-dominated 
Transitional Executive Council [TEC] to take over functions of 
the government, which it is doing," but "never expected it to 
show such arrogance and treat the government with such 
disrespect." The paper refers to the TEC's attempt to "stop 
Housing Minister Louis Shill from going ahead with his R90 
billion [rand] housing scheme for the low-income sector." The 
TEC is "setting itself up as a vehicle for ANC action against 
its enemies, including Chief Mangosuthu Buthelezi, the IFP 
[Inkatha Freedom Party] leader, and President Lucas Mangope of 
Bophuthatswana. This does not augur well for reconciliation and 
national unity, but suggests a dictatorial, aggressive attitude 
which can only exacerbate matters." 
<H6>  THE STAR </H6>
  Warning Against Postponing Election -- Johannesburg THE STAR 
in English on 11 March in a page-12 editorial notes that General 
Constand Viljoen of the Freedom Front, Lucas Mangope of 
Bophuthatswana, and the Inkatha Freedom Party's Mangosuthu 
Buthelezi want international mediation. "While such 
intervention implies neutral adjudication, it will not guarantee 
a satisfactory outcome, and will almost certainly (because of 
the time factor) require a postponement of the election. The 
country simply cannot afford that. If only out of 
considerations of security and reducing uncertainties, the poll 
must go ahead on April 27." 
<H6>  BUSINESS DAY </H6>
  SANCO Appoints Itself `Inquisitor' for ANC -- "Spotting an 
opportunity for power and influence, SANCO [South African 
National Civic Organization] has appointed itself the 
extra-parliamentary enforcer of the ANC's reconstruction and 
development programme," declares a page 6 editorial in 
Johannesburg BUSINESS DAY in English on 11 March. "It is now 
setting about stamping its undemocratic authority on a programme 
for which it is not accountable." "Last November, SANCO said it 
would investigate the operations of development agencies such as 
the Independent Development Trust and the SA Development Bank. 
Both of these operate with public funds and their activities 
can legitimately be questioned and directed by a new government; 
SANCO has appointed itself their inquisitor. In addition, it is 
now targeting private development agencies, the non-government 
organisations which raise and disburse money here, or which are 
channels of donations from abroad. SANCO is now determined to 
see that these funds, too, go where SANCO directs." BUSINESS DAY 
advises these agencies to "ignore these questions." "SANCO has 
no right to this information and replies may well lead to 
'suggestions' about changes in priorities or procedures." 
<H6>  WEEKLY MAIL &amp; GUARDIAN </H6>
  Call for Military Solution in Bophuthatswana -- Johannesburg 
WEEKLY MAIL &amp; GUARDIAN in English for 11-17 March says in a 
page-16 editorial it "does not, as a rule, favour military 
solutions to political problems" like the unrest in 
Bophuthatswana. "But there is a very real prospect that more 
lives may be lost, and the crisis in the homeland may spiral out 
of control, if De Klerk continues to stay his hand. What, after 
all, are the `South African interests' De Klerk says must be 
jeopardised before he will intervene? Are they not the two 
million people South Africa cut adrift when it granted 
Bophuthatswana independence, and who have the inalienable right 
to cast their votes in the country's first non-racial elections?" 
<H6>  CAPE TIMES </H6>
  Zimbabwe Government Abuse of Seized Land -- "The disclosure 
in our news columns that the first of 70 private farms seized by 
the Zimbabwe government ostensibly for peasant resettlement has 
in fact been allocated to a cabinet minister is yet another 
reminder of how government interference in the marketplace can 
be abused," warns a page-6 editorial in Cape Town CAPE TIMES in 
English on 9 March. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

