<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Violence Descends on Bophuthatswana as Government Flees </TI></H3>
<H4>   Residents Take to Streets </H4>
<F P=102> MB1003163394 Johannesburg SAPA in English 1621 GMT 10 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB1003163394 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Lew Elias] </F>
  [Text] Mmabatho March 10 SAPA -- Thousands of singing 
Bophuthatswana residents took to the streets of the capital 
Mmabatho on Thursday afternoon waving ANC [African National 
Congress] and SA Communist Party placards in what appeared to be 
the final signal that the homeland government had been toppled 
following almost a week of unrest. 
  Apart from the thousands of people running and toyi-toying 
[protest dancing] down the Lucas Mangope Highway, people in 
cars, minibuses and others piled on trucks were blaring horns 
and displaying the clenched fist black power salute. Police 
presence was at an absolute minimum with only three police cars 
seen hurrying towards [words indistinct] Bophuthatswana's 
reincorporation into South Africa. 
  Two Bop police Hippos outside the university in Mmabatho 
were 
all that remained of evidence of the intense confrontation 
between students and police in the past three days. The only 
policemen at the scene was standing on the armoured police 
personnel carrier and using the vehicle's public address system 
to repeat over and over: "We want peace". 
  Thousands of people headng towards an African National 
Congress [words indisticnt] were shouting: "We have done it. We 
have brought the government to its knees." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

