<F P=100> SOUTHERN AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Botswana </F>
<H3> <TI>   Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe Visits </TI></H3>
<H4>   Ends Four-Day Visit </H4>
<F P=102> MB1003184394 Gaborone Radio Botswana Network in English 1610 
GMT 10 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB1003184394 </F>
<F P=104>  Gaborone Radio Botswana Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] President Robert Mugabe of Zimbabwe left Gaborone 
this afternoon after a four-day visit to Botswana. He told 
journalists before his departure that he believed creating 
additional border posts, and involving local leaders and 
villages next to the Botswana-Zimbabwe border, could curb the 
problem of illegal border crossings. President Mugabe 
attributed the problem of illegal border crossings to 
unemployment, which he said is everywhere, even in Zimbabwe. He 
also admitted that a bureaucracy problem existed at the Zimbabwe 
Immigration Department, which he said hindered Batswana 
businessmen and women to do business. He promised that 
something would be done about it. 
  Commenting on the former Ethiopian leader's status in 
Zimbabwe, Mr. Mugabe said Mr. Mengistu Haile-Mariam sought 
refuge in Zimbabwe in accordance with international law. He 
said no extradition treaty exists between the two countries and 
in any case the treaty usually deals with individuals who commit 
crimes of a nonpolitical nature. 

</TEXT>

